    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2470765943" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2470765943" />
    <a title="Kes" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70325177-kes"><img alt="Kes" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2470765943?book_show_action=true">Jul 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kes" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kes" href="/user/show/70325177-kes">Kes</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19429492-weep-not-child">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70325177-kes?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70325177-kes?shelf=read-2018">read-2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2470765943" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14548354739552779118">3.5 stars<br/><br/>This feels like it would be nicer if consumed as an audiobook - as it is, the prose appears simple but feels like someone simply speaking to you.<br/><br/>This novella deals with a child going to school just as Kenya moves towards independence. We&apos;re introduced to the main character (Njoroge) as a child and the narrative maintains that child-like sense throughout the novella (until the end). Events happen; Njoroge is a passive bystander to them. Njoroge&apos;s brothers appear to be actors, and to some</span>
  <span id="freeText14548354739552779118" style="display:none">3.5 stars<br /><br />This feels like it would be nicer if consumed as an audiobook - as it is, the prose appears simple but feels like someone simply speaking to you.<br /><br />This novella deals with a child going to school just as Kenya moves towards independence. We're introduced to the main character (Njoroge) as a child and the narrative maintains that child-like sense throughout the novella (until the end). Events happen; Njoroge is a passive bystander to them. Njoroge's brothers appear to be actors, and to some extent, his father is too - but Njoroge maintains a strange, childlike passivity.<br /><br />We're introduced to Njoroge's family - his father, Ngotho, has two wives: Njeri and Nyokabi, who get along well. He has five sons (and several sisters; the sisters never really play a part in the novel). As Kenya fights for independence, Ngotho and his family are slowly drawn in. <br /><br />As someone unfamiliar with the background of this novel, the importance of race was startling. Indians were not liked "because their customs were strange and funny in a bad way". There are also the Europeans (whites). There appears to be some distinction between Africans and blacks, but I'm not sure about this either.<br /><br />There are so many background details - this is set just after the World War I &amp; II, and there's talk about blacks going to fight a white man's war. This is contrasted against the whites coming to appropriate black land (ancestral land) - for example, Ngotho lives on his ancestral land, but the land is officially held by Mr Howland, the white settler.<br /><br />The impact of colonialisation on Kenya underlies this book. First is the constant presence of education as a way up the social ladder (as opposed to trade - Njoroge's brother, Kamau, is apprenticed as a carpenter). <br /><br />Another is the importance of land as a means of wealth and security is another theme - through the observation that the only way to accrue wealth is through owning your own land, the fact that Ngotho was kicked off his ancestral land by Mr Howland after participating in the strike, and brings meaning to the impact of colonialisation on Ngotho's wealth.<br /><br />Third is that Njoroge is Christian - and meets Mwihaki in a church. This is something that is accepted; there is some localisation, but that is intriguing.<br /><br />Fourth, as Njeri observes:<br /><br /><blockquote>"It is more than that," said Njeri. "And although I am a woman and cannot explain it, it seems all clear as daylight. The white man makes a law or a rule. Through that rule or law or whatever you may call it, he takes away the land and then imposes many laws on the people concerning that land and many other things, all without people agreeing first as in the old days of the tribe. Now a man rises and opposes that law which made right the taking away of land. Now that man is taken by the same people who made the laws against which that man is fighting. He is tried under those alien rules. Now tell me who is that man who can win even if the angels of God were his lawyers... I mean."</blockquote><br /><br />As Njoroge's family vanishes - killed in the war, or <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[arrested by the colonialist due to their involvement in the resistance struggle <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, it feels like it parallels the fate of the African people. <br /><br />I also noticed the invisibility of women in this story - Njoroge's mothers remain a constant, perhaps invisible, presence. His sisters are unnamed (save having ugly names). Only Mwihaki has a presence.<br /><br />I really hated the open-ended ending. We leave with <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Njoroge bereft, with only his mothers - having contemplated suicide due to Mwihaki rejecting his call to run away from his duty. I choose to read it as happy - Njoroge recognises that he has more to live for and accepts his duty, especially with:<br /><br /><blockquote>Again Njoroge did not speak to Njeri, but felt only guilt, the guilt of a man who had avoided his responsibility for which he had prepared himself since childhood.</blockquote> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Lastly, a shout-out to this part:<br /><br /><blockquote>"What's a state of emergency?" a man asked.<br /><br />"Oh, don't ask a foolish question. Haven't you heard about Malaya?"<br /><br />"What about it?"<br /><br />"There was a state of emergency."</blockquote><br /><br />(I just love the unexpected reference to Southeast Asian history.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14548354739552779118" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

