    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2729299140" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2729299140" />
    <a title="Tony Wainaina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77208703-tony-wainaina"><img alt="Tony Wainaina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559493628p2/77208703.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2729299140?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tony Wainaina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tony Wainaina" href="/user/show/77208703-tony-wainaina">Tony Wainaina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2729299140" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4297169992852975455">I last read Ngugi when I was in school. Waaaay back. Decades ago. A set book. Grain of Wheat I think it was. But I have no recollection of the story at all. I’ve now set out, driven by free will rather than imposition, to read/re-read all of Ngugi’s works in 2019. A TW does a Ngugi wa Thiong’o retrospective kind of thing. <br/>Weep not Child was powerful for me. Starkly and vividly relatable because it was set at a time my parents were living under identical conditions during the Emergency in Central</span>
  <span id="freeText4297169992852975455" style="display:none">I last read Ngugi when I was in school. Waaaay back. Decades ago. A set book. Grain of Wheat I think it was. But I have no recollection of the story at all. I’ve now set out, driven by free will rather than imposition, to read/re-read all of Ngugi’s works in 2019. A TW does a Ngugi wa Thiong’o retrospective kind of thing. <br />Weep not Child was powerful for me. Starkly and vividly relatable because it was set at a time my parents were living under identical conditions during the Emergency in Central Kenya. Ngotho, Jacobo, Njoroge, Nyokabi, Isaka and Mwihaki are all real live characters I’ve heard about from my parents, uncles and aunts. Polygamy, Christianity, the pursuit of education, and the mish mashed confusion of it all within an apartheid system of the worst kind that broke families, decimated value systems that turned kinsmen into monstrous opponents.<br />There is so much yet understood, yet explained. The colonisation of Kenya, Christianity at the vanguard, mission education, mission health.The most successful, brilliantly executed mass confidence trickster event of all time??<br />The prose and pace resonated phonetically for me. Peppered with Kenyanisms. Comfort food. It was a must that Ngotho tilled Mr. Howland’s (how??? land indeed) land. Was it not Ngotho’s land after all?<br />If I had another shot at English Literature with Weep Not Child as a set book in my early teens primary school life, there could be no otherwise but for me to be number 1 in my class.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4297169992852975455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


